none: Tesoro sagro e venerabile cioé le basiliche, le chiese, i cimiterj, e i santuarj di Roma : con le opere di pietà e di religione che vi si esercitano da' fedeli secolari, e da' claustrali ancora negli oratorj, ospizj, e spedali, coi loro istituti ; e per ultimo del continuo concorso di Pellegrini illustri e Santi / raccolti e con brevità descritti da Giuseppe Vasi ... per disposizione ed apparecchio, del prossimo anno del Giubbileo MDCCLXXV.

Dedicated to the cardinal Lazzaro Opizio Pallavicini, secretary of State under Pope Clemens XIV, the Tesoro is a two volumes guidebook organized in eight giornate following the same structure of the Itinerario. Its focus is primarily on the sacred history of the Urbe (historia sacra) as declared by the elaborate frontispiece representing the Catholic church between the basilicas of Saint Peter and Saint John. Easily transportable, it was conceived to meet the needs of the pilgrims who would arrive in Rome shortly after its publication for the Jubilee year of 1775.

body.value: Piazza di San Lorenzo in Lucina is the square in front of San Lorenzo in Lucina, the church to which it owes its name.
Church of Santa Maria in Ara Coeli (named as Chiesa di S. Maria d’ Araceli)
Church of Santi Luca e Martina (named as Chiesa di Santa Martina). The entry mentions the Compagnia dei Pittori in 1588, but not the change of the name to Santi Luca e Martina.

Altemps Palace at Monte Cavallo. This guidebook reports Altemps Palace as belonging to its most recent owners, the Pallavicini-Rospigliosi family (about 1704–present). It does not mention the chain of previous owners: Scipione Borghese Caffarelli (1577–1633), about 1605–1616; Duke Giovanni Angelo Altemps (1587–1620), about 1616–1619; Guido Bentivoglio (1579–1644); Cardinal Giulio Mazarino (1602–1661), until about 1704; and the Pallavicini-Rospigliosi family (about 1704–present).
Church of Sant'Agata dei Goti. The Borgo di Sant'Agata was located in the vicinity of this church.

Church of Santa Maria Rotonda (Pantheon). The Pantheon became known as Sancta Maria ad Martyres in 609 CE, when Pope Boniface IV converted the pagan temple into a Christian basilica and moved the remains of many martyrs from the Christian catacombs to this site.
Church of San Nicola dei Lorenesi (named as Chiesa di S. Niccolò de’ Lorenesi)
